 never before, to follow specific themes and the role of individual participants. The narrative highlights key moments of stress, doubt, decision, and resolution—and even humor—and makes the meetings comprehensible both to readers who lived through the crisis and to those too young to remember the Cold War. Stern demonstrates that JFK, a seasoned Cold Warrior who bore some of the responsibility for precipitating the crisis, consistently steered policy makers away from an apocalyptic nuclear conflict, which he called, with stark eloquence, "the final failure."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150362428340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503624283423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503624283/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles